description.narrative:
The project’s activities are described below at three levels.

At individual level the project entails:
- the organisation of 60 FGM/C awareness sessions/campaigns in each governorate for 50 girls, young men, women and community leaders;
- 16 trainings on child rights, drama and theatre communication for 15 girls, children & youth clubs and FGM/C awareness associations, to help and support them in serving as community agents among their peers;
- 15 events like international days (women’s days, FGM/C Abandonment Day, Family Day) for awareness/public declaration campaigns.

At community level the project entails:
- eight Training of Trainer (ToT) sessions for 75 community promoters and volunteers, according to an FGM/C abandonment manual;
- eight specific trainings on harmful practices/FGM/C, advocacy and ToT for community leaders, medical workers, religious leaders etc.;
- eight specific trainings for healthcare staff, teachers and social workers in primary and preparatory schools, and family-counsellor training on pre-marriage awareness/counselling and reproductive health awareness and family-counselling skills;
-eight trainings for local organisations in four communities and four child protection committees on girls’ rights, child protection and FGM/C, as well as advocacy activities to support the project at a local level;
-eight exchange visits in which community members visit model villages where FGM/C has been eradicated; 
-16 meetings for the networks of local organisations that are working to counter violence against women/girls and harmful practices at governorate level.

At institutional level the project entails:
- quarterly  meetings for the national anti-FGM/C committee to follow-up on FGM/C law enforcement; 
- workshops on lobbying and advocacy efforts to enforce anti-FGM/C legislation, with participants from local organisations, key ministries and human rights activist at national and governorate levels;
- public-hearing sessions through community visit

To eliminate FGM/C, the social norms and values that fuel its continuation must be changed. Furthermore, legislation against FGM/C must be improved and enforced.  Men and boys will have to lobby for this and girls must be empowered to stand up for their sexual and reproductive health rights, and supported in doing so too. Individuals and local organisations are being trained to act as human rights defenders, meaning the project is tackling FGM/C at individual, community and institutional levels. In the context of this project: 
- girls, boys, and local youth and women’s groups are being empowered to oppose these violations and are being trained as human rights defenders;
- local development organisations, women’s groups and agents of change are lobbying to change the norms and values that justify and continue this harmful practice; 
- the legal and protection systems in the affected counties in Egypt are being strengthened and parliamentarians are being influenced.

All activities in the project are inter-connected and individual and community initiatives are being supported by a legal framework. Local organisations are playing a watchdog role in the case of violations that have already happened or are about to happen, and taking the necessary steps against these violations.
